The 9th Lagos State House of Assembly has since its inauguration on June 7, 2019 passed six bills into law. LEADERSHIP Investigation revealed that the bills include the Appropriation Amendment Law 2019 (Re-Ordering of Budget Priorities in 2019); Lagos State Audit Amendment Law; 2019, Appropriation Law, 2020; Land Use Charge (Amendment) Law 2020;  Lagos State Neighbourhood Safety Corps (Amendment) Law, 2020 and Coronavirus Pandemic Law. Speaking on this development, Hon.Mojisola Alli Macaulay said the passage of bills, resolutions and motions were not the parameter used in assessing the performance of the legislative arm of government because it is events that spurs bills passed. According to her, “So far so good the 9th Assembly of Lagos State has in the last one year delivered on its obligations and worked hard to ensure a conducive environment is created for business development.’’ She pointed out that bills, resolutions and motions that touched the lives of constituents are moved to support the executive arm of government. The lawmaker who represents Amuwo Odofin Constituency 1 said, “When the fire incident at Abule Ado Festac Town, Amuwo- Odofin Local government area occurred on March 15, this year I moved a motion in the floor of the House urging Governor Babajide Sanwo-Olu to set up a committee to investigate immediate cause of the gas explosion. ‘’The motion also entails that culprits found culpable should be prosecuted so as to serve a deterrent to others while Nigerian National Petroleum Commission (NNPC), Department of Petroleum Resources (DPR) should ensure strict compliance with the rights of way relating to the construction of buildings.’’ Macaulay also said the governor was enjoined to direct the Commissioner, Ministry of Physical Planning and Urban Development to investigate the construction of buildings on the pipeline corridors within Abule-Ado, Festac Town without approval of the government. Regarding prospects in the second year of the 9th assembly she said the House will only move motions and pass resolutions and bills that will touch the lives of Lagosians.  